(3, ' Vietnams seafood exports set to grow 6.3 percent this year', ' Vietnams-seafood-exports-set-to-grow-6.3-percent-this-year', '<p>New free trade deals with EU and Asian markets are expected to increase Vietnam&rsquo;s seafood exports to more than US$7 billion this year, a trade group said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Truong Dinh Hoe, general secretary of Vietnam Association of Seafood Exporters and Processors, said at a recent meeting in the Mekong Delta&rsquo;s Can Tho that exports in 2016 are expected to grow 6.3 percent from last year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Half of the revenue will come from shrimp exports, which are poised to increase around 12 percent, Hoe said, as cited by the Saigon Times Online.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Benefits from free trade pacts with EU, Japan, South Korea and ASEAN neighbors will help Vietnam weather the tough competition from&nbsp;Ecuador, India, Indonesia and Thailand, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tuna exports are also expected to rise 8 percent from last year, and squid and octopus shipments 10 percent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vietnamese seafood businesses had a bad year in 2015 when exports dropped 14.5 percent from the previous year to $6.7 billion.&nbsp;Hot weather and low prices prompted businesses to scale down their operation, according to insiders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year businesses have been expecting a strong recovery brought by new free trade deals, as well as prospects of&nbsp;the upcoming Trans Pacific Partnership. Twelve countries in the pact, including the US and Japan,&nbsp;set to reduce or eliminate 90 percent of import tariffs.</p>\r\n', 'public/site/images/6/shrimp_YWGA.jpg', '', 'Shrimp shipments are expected to account for nearly half of total earnings of more than $7 billion', '', 0, 0, '', 6, 'Bussiness', 'bussiness', 10, '2016-04-24 20:04:30', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0),
(4, 'Dilma Rousseff Was Not Impeached, Legal Scholars Say', 'dilma-rousseff-was-not-impeached-legal-scholars-say', '<p>Brazilians and many others are transfixed over the impeachment proceedings against Dilma Rousseff, the first female president of Brazil. But while impeachment is not uncommon, not every country agrees on what it means.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lawmakers in at least a half-dozen countries, from Iran to the United States, have subjected their leaders to impeachment in recent decades. And not every case turned out badly for the politician who was targeted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the United States, two presidents have been impeached &mdash; Andrew Johnson in 1868 and Bill Clinton in 1998 &mdash; but the rules required neither to step aside during their trials. Both were acquitted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But in Brazil, Ms. Rousseff has not yet been impeached, legal scholars say.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;In Brazil, the term impeachment is used only after a conviction is made in the trial,&rdquo; said Daniel Vargas, a law professor at Funda&ccedil;&atilde;o Getulio Vargas in Rio de Janeiro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now that Brazil&rsquo;s Senate voted against her on Thursday, Ms. Rousseff will have to step aside during her impeachment trial, which could last for six months. But if she is ultimately absolved, she will not have been impeached, Mr. Vargas said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Others agreed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Formally speaking, she has not yet been impeached,&rdquo; said Ronaldo Porto Macedo Jr., a law professor at the University of S&atilde;o Paulo and other institutions. &ldquo;She is only considered impeached when there&rsquo;s a final judgment.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Rousseff is not the first Brazilian president to confront impeachment. In 1992, Fernando Collor de Mello&nbsp;<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/30/world/brazilian-leader-quits-as-his-trial-starts-in-senate.html">resigned</a>&nbsp;just as his trial in the Senate began. He was found guilty and barred from elected office for eight years.</p>\r\n', 'public/site/images/1/13IMPEACH-web1-master768.jpg', '', 'Not every nation agrees on what an impeachment means. And not each case turns out badly for the defendant, as several recent cases have demonstrated', '', 0, 0, '', 1, 'world', 'world', 9, '2016-05-12 16:24:11', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0),
(5, 'Pope Says Hes Open to Studying Whether Women Can Serve as Deacons', 'pope-says-hes-open-to-studying-whether-women-can-serve-as-deacons', '<p>ROME &mdash;&nbsp;<a href="http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/f/francis_i/index.html?inline=nyt-per">Pope Francis</a>&nbsp;suggested on Thursday that he was open to studying whether women can serve as deacons in the&nbsp;<a href="http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/r/roman_catholic_church/index.html?inline=nyt-org">Roman Catholic Church</a>, revealing an openness &mdash; if nothing else &mdash; to re-examining the church&rsquo;s long-held insistence on an all-male clergy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The pope&rsquo;s comments were made during an assembly of leaders of female Catholic religious congregations, and were consistent with his off-the-cuff style: a seemingly impromptu remark that opened a broad horizon of possibilities and, perhaps, long-held hopes by Catholic women who have clamored to play a more incisive role in the traditionally male institution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During a discussion at the Vatican on Thursday, which at one point touched on the role that women deacons played during the early years of the church, Francis responded to someone who asked about the possibility of an official commission to study the question. His response was, in essence, &ldquo;Why not?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Set up an official commission that could study this question,&rdquo; Pope Francis mused out loud, the ANSA news agency reported. &ldquo;I think, yes. It would be good for the church to clarify this point. I agree. I will do something of the sort.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ANSA also reported that the pope appeared uncertain about the actual role that women deacons had in the first years of the church, and whether they were ordained or not. A commission could help clarify such issues, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Deacons are ordained ministers in the Roman Catholic Church, and in many parishes they perform many of the roles entrusted to priests. They are permitted to preach at Mass, baptize, witness marriages and conduct funeral services. They must be men over the age of 35, and they may be married (though if a deacon&rsquo;s wife dies, he is expected to remain celibate).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The church in the United States has been actively encouraging men to become deacons to assist priests stretched thin because of a shortage of priests. The&nbsp;<a href="http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/u/united_states_conference_of_catholic_bishops/index.html?inline=nyt-org">United States Conference of Catholic Bishops</a>&nbsp;says there are now more than 13,000 men serving in what is called the &ldquo;permanent diaconate.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is not the first time the issue of female deacons has come up. In 1995, an American group of canon law experts&nbsp;<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/12/us/expert-panel-on-catholic-church-law-backs-women-as-deacons.html">said that&nbsp;</a><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/1995/11/12/us/expert-panel-on-catholic-church-law-backs-women-as-deacons.html">ordaining women as deacons in the church</a>&nbsp;would be in keeping with Catholic theology and past practice, though the Vatican never acted on that recommendation. The topic has continued to come up in discussions, however: Just last week, for example, scholars met at the University of Toronto for a&nbsp;<a href="https://stmikes.utoronto.ca/event/women-the-diaconate-and-the-future-of-ministry-a-study-day-at-the-faculty-of-theology/">conference</a>entitled: &ldquo;Women, the Diaconate, and the Future of Ministry.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Groups who have pushed for women to play a greater role in the church welcomed the pope&rsquo;s declarations, as an important &mdash; if embryonic &mdash; step.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Rev. James Bretzke, a professor of theology at Boston College, said in a statement, &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t underscore enough how groundbreaking this is for the Church.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Father Bretzke, who, like Pope Francis, is a member of the Jesuit religious order, added, &ldquo;If women can be ordained as deacons, then this is going to weaken &mdash; not destroy &mdash; but weaken significantly the argument that women absolutely are incapable of being ordained as priests. So this is opening more than a crack in the door.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Women&rsquo;s Ordination Conference, an American organization that supports the ordination of women as deacons, priests and bishops, said in a statement: &ldquo;Opening a commission to study the diaconate for women would be a great step for the Vatican in recognizing its own history.&rdquo;</p>\r\n', 'public/site/images/1/46456456.jpg', '', 'The off-the-cuff remark was far from a change in doctrine, but opened a conversation on a pressing issue.', '', 0, 0, '', 1, 'world', 'world', 9, '2016-05-12 16:26:06', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, 0);

